@node "Description" "Description - AltNTab? I hear you say!"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Main"
                             @{fg fill}AltNTab 1.0@{fg text}
                  © 1996 Brain Destruction Software
                          Written by Burnsy

@{b}Description:-@{ub}

This is a small @{"commodity" link "Commodity" 0} program which controls the order or your windows
in much the same way that the @{"depth" link "Depth" 0} button does, although with less control.
AltNTab cycles through the windows, rather than bringing a particular one to
the front.

I know some people may be scared of what this does to the Amiga to obtain
this.  Well it does nothing I would class as illegal.  It does not hack into
anything.  The program sets up a commodity @{"broker" link "Broker" 0} from which you can control
it, but mainly to give AltNTab a safe and reliable way to recieve a @{"hotkey" link "HotKey" 0}.
Once it recives the hotkey (which can be set up by you), it finds out which
is the Active Window, then tells @{"intuition" link "Intuition" 0} to bring the next window to the
front.  If the active window is the last window in the list, it then returns
to the begining of the list.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage - How to use this work of art!"
@next "Reason"
@prev "Description"
                             @{fg fill}AltNTab 1.0@{fg text}
                  © 1996 Brain Destruction Software
                          Written by Burnsy

@{b}Usage:-@{ub}

AltNTab is very easy to use.  It accepts only two arguments, either from the
@{"CLI prompt" link "CLI" 0} or from the @{"Tool Types" link "ToolTypes" 0}.  These arguments are...

@{b}CX_PRIORITY @{ub}       - The priority you wish the commodity to run at.

@{b}HOTKEY@{ub}             - The key sequence you wish to use for the window
                     switching.

Both arguments are optional, and have their defaults.  If no CX_Priority is
specified then it defaults to 0.  If no @{"HotKey" link "HotKey" 0} is specified it defaults to
"ALT TAB" :) Once the program is up and running it is invisable to the user,
until it recieves it's HotKey, then it will switch to the next window. To
quit the program, either run it again, or use Commodities @{"Exchange" link "Exchange" 0} to remove
it.
@endnode

@node "Reason" "Reason - Why should PC owners have it and not us!"
@next "Other"
@prev "Usage"
                             @{fg fill}AltNTab 1.0@{fg text}
                  © 1996 Brain Destruction Software
                          Written by Burnsy

Reason:-

When you have more than one screen open you can use @{b}LEFT AMIGA + M@{ub} to switch
between them, this is very handy is you are using the keyboard, since you
don't have to reach for the mouse.  PC Windows users don't have seperate
screens (mustn't have nicked that yet :)), but can use @{b}ALT + TAB@{ub} to switch
between windows.  So I thought why not write one for the Amiga, surely it
would be helpful to be able to switch windows with a key or two?  Well I
find it usefull, hope you do :)
@endnode

