@node "Commodity" "Reference - Commodity"
@{fg highlight}Commodity@{fg text}

A commodity is a program which makes use of the standard commodities library
to gain it's input, rather than installing it's own input handler.  This
provides a safe way for the program to recieve input, and an easy way for
the user to interact with the program using @{"Exchange" link "Exchange" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Depth" "Reference - Depth Gadget"
@{fg highlight}Depth Gadget:@{fg text}

The small gadget in the top right hand corner of most windows, if you click
on this gadget then it will arrange the depth of the window, either bringing
it to the front or sending it to the back, depending on its current state.
@endnode

@node "Broker" "Reference - Broker"
@{fg highlight}Broker@{fg text}

A commodities broker is the interface a program launches to @{"Exchange" link "Exchange" 0}. Once
this has been initiated, Exchange will add your program to it's list, where
it can pass on various information from you.
@endnode

@node "HotKey" "Reference - HotKey"
@{fg highlight}HotKey@{fg text}

A hotkey, is a combination of keypresses that can be used to activate
something.  A hotkey can be something simple like "T", so when the T key is
pressed on the keyboard then the hotkey will be recieved, or as complicated
as "rawmouse rbutton lbutton mouse_leftpress".
@endnode

@node "Intuition" "Reference - Intuition"
@{fg highlight}Intuition@{fg text}

Intuition is the system that handles all drawing to the screen in Workbench
mode.  It handles all screens, windows, gadgets, menus, etc.
@endnode

@node "Exchange" "Reference - Exchange"
@{fg highlight}Exchange@{fg text}

The Exchange program can be located in your Tools/Commodities drawer, and
will enable you to control all commodity applications.
@endnode

@node "CLI" "Reference - CLI Prompt"
@{fg highlight}CLI@{fg text}

The CLI (Command Line Interface) is another way of interacting with the
Amiga.  This can be activated either from booting, by not using loadwb, or
can be re-opened using the Shell icon located in the System drawer.
@endnode

@node "ToolTypes" "Reference - Tool Types"
@{fg highlight}ToolTypes@{fg text}

ToolTypes are used to pass information to an application using it's icon.
Select a tool icon, then select Information from the Icons menu. In the
window that appears is a box which contains the tooltypes for that program.
@endnode

